thread.title: Portland State Vikings make history, knock off North Texas 66-7
thread.title_full: Portland State Vikings make history, knock off North Texas 66-7 | OregonLive.com

author: Oregonian/OregonLive Sports
title: Portland State Vikings make history, knock off North Texas 66-7
text:
Portland State made history as it routed North Texas 66-7 on Saturday in Denton, Texas.
The Vikings' athletic department reports the game's 59-point margin is the biggest ever by a Football Championship Subdivision team over a Football Bowl Subdivision opponent. PSU reported the previous largest margin was Lehigh's 58-point win over Penn in 1981.
North Texas athletic director Rick Villarreal fired football coach Dan McCarney after the loss, which dropped the Mean Green of Conference USA to 0-5 on the season.
The 25th-ranked Vikings (4-1, 1-1 Big Sky Conference) had 670 yards of total offense, and bounced back after losing 19-17 at home to conference foe North Dakota last Saturday.
Portland State also notched its second victory over an FBS opponent, the first time in program history the Vikings have done that in a season. PSU knocked off Washington State 24-17 in Pullman to open the season.
Against North Texas, Vikings quarterback Alex Kuresa threw for 269 yards and had scoring strikes of 34, 56 and 60 yards. David Jones ran for two touchdowns, including a 70-yarder, and finished with 134 yards on nine carries. Kuresa connected with Jones on the 60-yard touchdown pass two plays after the second-half kickoff.
Nate Tago ran for two touchdowns, and Steven Long ran for one. Darnell Adams and Thomas Carter III had touchdown catches.
With about a minute to play, DaMarcus Smith threw a 9-yard touchdown pass to Carlos Harris for North Texas (0-5). The Mean Green finished with just 198 yards of offense.
Information from The Associated Press was used in this report.
